segments.text: influenced some of the decisions that made A&M a better institution.
All right.
Can you think on that?
Can you think of any time when the decision was in the lurch and some individual, you or somebody else, may have at a key moment made that decision?
Work?

Well, I guess in some ways it has to, I'm thinking several, because one of the lines that I used with a lot of prospective faculty members was that the thing I liked, one of the things I liked the most about ADN was that generally the administration, when you propose something to them, their first response was likely to be, let's see how we can make that work.
And then after you looked into it carefully, there were times that you came up and said, we can't.
But I found that so much more satisfying than saying, well, you know, why don't we?
No, no, we've already done that before, and it didn't work, and we don't have the money to do it.
So, you know, we just can't even think about that.
At least let me finish my sentence and say what I think we ought to think about.
No, we just can't do it.
So again, I talked about some of the programs, tectonophysics and the nautical archeology program.
There were so many programs that A&M got involved with that most universities couldn't have done.
And the available fund was a critical factor in allowing us to do a lot of things.
As you remember when you were here, Haskell, there were a lot of years that we were teaching more students without state subvention than were being taught at Prairie View and Tarleton combined.
And we had a lot of growth and I think it was a, I think we did not lose a lot in the quality of what we were doing.
But I think a lot of schools would have just been
suffering from trying to do because of the resources we had and the support we had from the administration.
And a lot of the board members were very pleased to see us grow.
I remember, and you were involved a lot, I know, in trying to figure out how in the world we could ever get over the 20,000.
How can we get to where we'll have 20,000 students?
We'll beat the Bushes, and we'll do this, and we'll do that.
And then when they came, they came in a rush.
Just two or three more things.
Can you think of any, as you look back, can you think of any event or decision with the benefit of hindsight, if you could have had omnipotence, at that point, do you go back and change that one?
The one I guess I would achieve that I had nothing to do with it would be giving up the part of the state.
I think that from a system point of view that was... What about any here?
Be it personnel decisions or academic decisions?
Well there are certainly some personnel decisions that I would have done differently but those are value judgments.
I think I'll pass on those.
As you look back, which are the dearest parts of the university to your heart?
Which parts do you care most about?
I guess, again, for a single event, the one that was most moving to me is Silver Taps.
I just think that makes A&M truly unique as far as I know.
I think a lot of the traditions of A&M are still very important.

The thing that I fear we are not doing as well today, or they're not doing as well today, is the real concern for the undergrad students that seems to be less important today than it has been in the past.
And I have believed for a long while that
that administrators, university administrators, are really short-sighted.
When they don't recognize that the best advertisement you get is a well-qualified, employed, satisfied graduate.
And they're going to become taxpayers and some of them become legislators.
And if they have very positive memories about their higher education experience, it's going to be a lot better.
If they have very negative experiences, then they're going to pay a price sooner or later.
And one of the things that I've probably inflicted on you that I really think has some substance is that intrastate your reputation built on high quality undergraduate education and applied research.
But nationally and internationally, it's on basic research and graduate education.
And so when you try to plug in both audiences, it's tough.
But it's something I think can be done.
And I think, again, A&M has the resources to do both.
I don't think it has to be either or.
Which unit or part or department of the campus do you care most about and kind of keep in touch with how it's progressing if you read the paper or talk to people?
But one of the things that I believe is true is that I always had a concern for the entire university.
I never felt parochial, and that's a strength and a weakness because even when I had nothing to do, I was still interested in the student life.
I think that's very important, the second curriculum and all those things.
even though I had no direct involvement.
But I always admired the history department.
I'm not saying it's because you're here.
But for a long time, I think it was generally conceded that the best teaching in the university was done in the history department.
But even when I had nothing to do with history, I admired the fact that there was really high quality teaching done in the history department.
I am certainly not a scientist nor an engineer, but I take great pride in the reputation of science and engineering at Texas A&M.
I take great pride in the reputation I think the vet school has had.
So again, I'd like to live in the reflected glory of A&M.
And so I want them to do whatever they do well.
And one of the things, again, I think you and I talked about, I just like when people think of A&M as a class place.
Last, your favorite Aggie story.
My favorite Aggie story is at the adjunct when I was the director.
At that point, we sent out mid-six weeks grades.
So at the end of the three weeks, we sent out grades.
We had a kid named Jack Abbott from down in the valley.
really nice young man, not a great student.
And he was not doing well.
And as soon as the male could get to the valley and the woman could drive up in a big, big Cadillac, she was there.
And she came in and she was very, very nicely dressed.
And she came in to see me to talk about her son.
So I told her, I said, you know, Jack is a really fine young man, and he is a good hurdler, but I really don't believe he's ready for Texas A&M right now.
And she said, well, what do you think he ought to do?
And I said, well, you know, that's got to be his choice and your choice.
But if you ask me, I would think it might be worthwhile for him to consider a good community college and get the basic courses, a little more maturity,
get him to his major where he'd be more interested and do better.
Which junior college do you think he ought to go to?
You know, that's your choice.
But I said, you know, since you've asked, I'll take it.
The students from Blinn have tended to do well when they transferred to Indian.
I said, they've got that two-timing approach over there, and they run a pretty tight ship that's close to Indian.
They get to visit friends, be involved.
I said, so that would be one he might want to consider.
And she said, Dr. McKinney, I don't care who my son marries.
And I don't care what church he attends.
But he will graduate from Texas A&M.
And he did.
He went to Blinn.
I heard he got sick over there.
His mother grew up in the valley.
Ran two motel rooms.
She got all his homework assignments.
Helped him all that.
And he came over here, ran track, lettered.
He graduated, but I'll never forget that line.
I don't care who he marries or what church he attends, but he will graduate from Texas A&M.
Thank you.
